younger artists that tell me that they want to be &quot;just like Joe Mad or Michael Turner.&quot;  That sickens me.  Originality seems to be lacking in the future art world and I just hope that the people who do claw hard enough to get to the top are the ones who stay original.<br>
Futura <p>2000, Detroit:  A woman stopped at a light noticed that the car in front of her had a "honk if you love Jesus" bumper sticker on it, she proceeded to honk her horn with gusto.  The man in front of her got out and proceeded to in turn bash the windshield and hood of her car to smithereens.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uwhitemage.showPublicProfile?language=EN>WhiteMage</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/6/02 9:12:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=10187.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.sphosting.com/darkhalo/GIR4.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Drawing Styles???</span><hr size=1> I think personal style is something that comes with time.  It's that little bit of yourself that finds its way into your work, and I think if you just concentrate on getting your fundamentals down first, style will happen naturally.   <p><font size="1">----------
